install.packages("tidyverse")
library(tidyverse)

1)

a) Read in (from the URL) and display (some of) the dataframe. How many observations and variables are there?

url = "http://ritsokiguess.site/datafiles/gss-cat.csv"
gss_cat <- read_csv(url)
Rows: 21407 Columns: 9
 Column specification 
Delimiter: ","
chr (6): marital, race, rincome, partyid, relig, denom
dbl (3): year, age, tvhours

 Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
 Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
head(gss_cat)

So, by the Rows: 21407 and Columns: 9 in R Console, number of observations = 21407, variables = 9.

b) Display only the column that contains marital status.

gss_cat %>% select(marital)

c) Display all the quantitative columns, without naming any columns.

gss_cat %>% select(where(is.numeric))

d) Display only the observations for the 2012 survey.

gss_cat %>% filter(year==2012)

e) For the people in the 2012 survey, how many of them were divorced, and what was the mean and standard deviation of age for those people? (I do not want to see anything about people in other years of survey or any other marital status.)

gss_cat %>% filter(year==2012) %>%
  filter(marital=="Divorced") %>%
summarise(number_of_people = n(),mean = mean(age),sd = sd(age))

In 2012, 316 people were divorced, mean of age is 54.00949 and standard deviation is 13.13024.

2)

a)Read in and display some of the population.

url = "http://ritsokiguess.site/datafiles/thepop.csv"
lln <- read_csv(url)
Rows: 1000 Columns: 1
 Column specification 
Delimiter: ","
dbl (1): y

 Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
 Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
head(lln)

b) Draw a histogram of the population. What do you see from the histogram?

ggplot(data = lln, aes(x = y)) + geom_histogram(bins=10)

The data is observably and strongly skewed to the right.

c) Draw a large number of samples of size 5 without replacement from this population, work out the mean of each one, and make a plot of the means.

tibble(sim = 1:1000) %>%
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(sample = list(sample(lln$y, size = 5,replace = FALSE))) %>%
  mutate(my_mean_t = mean(sample)) %>%ggplot(aes(x=my_mean_t))+geom_histogram(bins=10)

d) Repeat the previous part for samples of size 20.

tibble(sim = 1:1000) %>%
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(sample = list(sample(lln$y, size = 20,replace = FALSE))) %>%
  mutate(my_mean_t = mean(sample)) %>%ggplot(aes(x=my_mean_t))+geom_histogram(bins=10)

e) Repeat the previous part for samples of size 100.

tibble(sim = 1:1000) %>%
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(sample = list(sample(lln$y, size = 100,replace = FALSE))) %>%
  mutate(my_mean_t = mean(sample)) %>%ggplot(aes(x=my_mean_t))+geom_histogram(bins=10)

f) Explain as briefly as possible how your simulations illustrate the Law of Large Numbers.

lln %>% summarise(mean(y))

The LLN states As the sample size becomes large, the sample mean is going to have a higher probability of approaching the population mean. And from c) to e) ,as the sample size increasing, there are more sample means near the population mean 3.05. MeanwhileThe distribution of data is also more centralized.
